baseline_foam_map.py README




Reference to the Master Equation



Map the Solar System + 10 AU into interstellar space
Grid spans [-10 AU, +10 AU] in each Cartesian direction (R_MAX_AU = 20 AU).
The spatial domain is a direct geometric choice; the baseline foam density ρ_f (Eq. 3.2) is defined everywhere in this domain.


Baseline spacetime‑foam matrix
Uniform arrays for ρ_f, σ_f, η_f, scalar foam ϕ, temporal index n_t, strain = 0, energy = 0.
Eq. 3.2 (foam fluid properties), Eq. 3.1 (scalar foam field), Eq. 6.1 (temporal refractive index), Eq. 5.17 (foam energy – zero for undisturbed case).


Sandbox for future data
The FoamMap object can be mutated (foam.density[...] = new_value) or extended with extra layers (e.g. a “distortion” field).
The reference’s “driven” equations (e.g. §5.7 Mathieu‑type, §5.30 foam mode dynamics) can later write into these arrays.


Query by coordinates
FoamMap.get_foam_at(x, y, z) returns a dict of all baseline quantities for any spacecraft position.
Future navigation code can call this routine to obtain the “local” foam state, exactly as required by the Navigator Mathematics (§8).


Read foam distortions (baseline = none)
The returned strain and energy fields are zero, matching the “no‑disturbance” assumption.
Eq. 3.4 (warp velocity from strain) would return zero because strain = 0.


Stream to another program for 3‑D rendering
FoamStreamingServer opens a TCP socket, sends a JSON header, then streams each XY‑plane as a JSON‑lines message. Any open‑source visualiser (Blender‑Python, Godot, three‑js, ParaView, etc.) can connect, parse the slices, and build a volumetric texture.
The streaming protocol is deliberately simple so it can be added to the “EM detection & navigation” pipeline (§11) without needing a custom binary format.


Self‑contained, single file
All logic lives in baseline_foam_map.py; only standard libraries plus numpy are required.
No external assets; the file can be version‑controlled alongside the rest of the framework.



Extending the sandbox

Adding measured distortions – after a measurement campaign you can load a 3‑D NumPy array Δϕ_meas and simply do foam.scalar_foam += Δϕ_meas. All query calls will automatically return the updated values.
Higher‑resolution regions – create a second FoamMap with a smaller spacing_au (e.g. 0.01 AU) for a region around a wormhole throat, then stitch the two grids together in the visualiser.
Coupling to the Navigator – the Navigator equations (§8) use the foam gradient ∇ϕ. You can compute it on‑the‑fly with np.gradient(foam.scalar_foam, foam.spacing_m) and feed the result into a navigation controller.
